# How Does Deforestation Cause Climate Change?  
## A Comprehensive Analysis

---

### Introduction

Deforestation, the large-scale removal of forest cover, is a critical environmental issue with profound implications for global climate change. Forests act as vital carbon sinks, absorbing carbon dioxide (CO2) from the atmosphere through photosynthesis and storing it in biomass and soils. The destruction of forests not only releases stored carbon but also disrupts the natural processes that regulate atmospheric CO2 levels and local climate systems. This report provides an in-depth examination of how deforestation contributes to climate change, integrating scientific data, mechanisms, and impacts, supported by recent research and authoritative sources.

---

### The Role of Forests in the Carbon Cycle and Climate Regulation

Forests cover approximately 31% of the Earth's land area and play a pivotal role in the global carbon cycle. Trees absorb CO2, a major greenhouse gas, converting it into organic carbon stored in trunks, branches, leaves, roots, and soil. This process mitigates the greenhouse effect by reducing atmospheric CO2 concentrations. Tropical forests alone are responsible for sequestering vast amounts of carbon, with the Amazon rainforest containing biomass carbon exceeding ten years’ worth of carbon emissions from human activities ([EarthLabs](https://serc.carleton.edu/earthlabs/climate/4a.html)).

Forests also influence climate through biophysical processes such as evapotranspiration, which cools the atmosphere by releasing water vapor, and albedo effects, which affect the Earth's reflectivity. Tropical and temperate forests generally have a cooling effect due to high evapotranspiration, while boreal forests may have a warming effect because of their lower albedo compared to snow-covered surfaces ([Alkama & Cescatti, 2016](https://science.sciencemag.org/content/351/6273/600)).

---

### Mechanisms by Which Deforestation Causes Climate Change

#### 1. **Carbon Emissions from Forest Loss**

When forests are cleared or burned, the carbon stored in trees and soil is released into the atmosphere primarily as CO2. This release occurs through combustion and decomposition of biomass and soil organic matter. Tropical deforestation alone contributed about 2.6 billion tonnes of CO2 annually between 2010 and 2014, accounting for roughly 6.5% of global CO2 emissions ([Wikipedia, 2020](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deforestation_and_climate_change)).

Globally, deforestation is responsible for approximately 11% of greenhouse gas emissions as of 2019, making it the second-largest anthropogenic source after fossil fuel combustion ([Wikipedia, 2020](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deforestation_and_climate_change)). The carbon emissions from tropical deforestation are accelerating, exacerbating climate change ([Feng et al., 2022](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41893-022-00854-3)).

| **Source**                  | **Annual CO2 Emissions (Billion Tonnes)** | **Percentage of Global Emissions** |
|-----------------------------|-------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------|
| Tropical Deforestation (2010-2014) | 2.6                                       | 6.5%                              |
| Total Deforestation (2019)          | ~4.8 (tropical forests)                    | 11% (all deforestation)            |
| Fossil Fuel Combustion              | >30                                       | ~70%                             |

#### 2. **Disruption of Carbon Sequestration**

Deforestation reduces the capacity of forests to absorb CO2. Growing forests act as carbon sinks, but when trees are removed, this sink function diminishes. Intact forests sequester carbon continuously, but deforestation disrupts this process, leading to a positive feedback loop where increased atmospheric CO2 leads to warming, which in turn can increase deforestation rates through droughts and wildfires ([Earth Eclipse](https://eartheclipse.com/environment/deforestation-and-climate-change/)).

#### 3. **Biophysical Effects: Albedo and Evapotranspiration**

Deforestation changes the land surface’s reflectivity (albedo) and water cycling. For example, clearing tropical forests reduces evapotranspiration, leading to less cloud formation and increased surface temperatures. Conversely, boreal deforestation increases albedo due to snow exposure, potentially causing local cooling but contributing to global warming overall when considering carbon emissions ([Alkama & Cescatti, 2016](https://science.sciencemag.org/content/351/6273/600)).

#### 4. **Emission of Short-Lived Climate Forcers (SLCFs)**

Forests emit biogenic volatile organic compounds (BVOCs) that influence the formation of aerosols, ozone, and methane—short-lived climate forcers affecting radiative forcing. Deforestation reduces BVOC emissions, altering atmospheric chemistry. A study by Scott et al. (2018) found that global deforestation results in a net positive radiative forcing of 0.12 W/m² from SLCFs, contributing to an estimated 0.8 K warming after 100 years, with SLCFs accounting for 8% of this effect ([Scott et al., 2018](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-017-02412-4)).

