### Causes and Drivers of Deforestation

Understanding the causes of deforestation is essential to grasp its impact on climate change.

| **Cause**              | **Description**                                                                                  | **Impact on Deforestation**                        |
|------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------|
| Lumber Industry        | Harvesting timber for wood products; about 4 million hectares harvested annually (1.3% forest land) | Direct removal of trees; carbon emissions from processing (~15%) |
| Agricultural Expansion | Conversion of forests to plantations (coffee, palm oil, soy, etc.) and cropland                  | Largest driver; >80% of deforestation linked to agriculture |
| Livestock Ranching     | Clearing land for grazing; significant methane emissions from cattle                             | Major contributor, especially in Amazon            |
| Palm Oil Production    | Expansion in tropical regions; demand expected to double by 2050                               | Significant deforestation in Indonesia and Malaysia |
| Urbanization           | Clearing forests for housing and infrastructure                                                | Minor but growing driver                            |
| Slash-and-Burn Farming| Temporary clearing for subsistence agriculture, leading to soil degradation                     | Accounts for ~30% of global arable land             |

Agricultural expansion, particularly for cattle ranching and commodity crops like palm oil and soy, is the predominant cause of deforestation globally ([Wikipedia, 2020](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deforestation_and_climate_change)).

---

### Effects of Deforestation on Climate and Environment

#### 1. **Global and Regional Temperature Changes**

Deforestation leads to increased surface temperatures, especially in tropical and arid zones, due to reduced evapotranspiration and changes in albedo. Observational data show that forest loss amplifies diurnal temperature variation and increases mean and maximum air temperatures, with the largest warming in arid zones (~2°C increase) and temperate/tropical zones (~1°C increase) ([Alkama & Cescatti, 2016](https://science.sciencemag.org/content/351/6273/600)).

#### 2. **Feedback Loops**

Climate change effects such as increased wildfires and droughts further accelerate deforestation, creating a positive feedback loop that exacerbates global warming ([Wikipedia, 2020](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deforestation_and_climate_change)).

#### 3. **Loss of Biodiversity**

Deforestation leads to habitat loss and fragmentation, threatening biodiversity hotspots that contain 20% of the Earth's flora. Loss of biodiversity reduces the ecosystem's ability to sequester carbon, worsening climate change impacts ([Wikipedia, 2020](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deforestation_and_climate_change)).

#### 4. **Soil and Water Impacts**

Clearing forests alters soil properties, reducing water retention and increasing susceptibility to erosion and fire. This leads to hotter, drier local climates and disrupts water cycles, further impacting regional climate and ecosystems ([Wikipedia, 2020](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deforestation_and_climate_change)).

---

### Quantifying the Contribution of Deforestation to Climate Change

- Tropical deforestation accounts for about 10% of global CO2 emissions, with total deforestation and forest degradation possibly contributing up to 15% when including peatland emissions ([Union of Concerned Scientists, 2013](https://www.ucsusa.org/resources/measuring-role-deforestation-global-warming)).

- The annual loss of forest area is approximately 75,700 square kilometers (18.7 million acres), with a 12% increase in primary tropical forest loss from 2019 to 2020 ([Wikipedia, 2020](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deforestation_and_climate_change)).

- The carbon released from deforestation is equivalent to the emissions of hundreds of millions of cars annually, underscoring its significance in global emissions ([Union of Concerned Scientists, 2013](https://www.ucsusa.org/resources/measuring-role-deforestation-global-warming)).

---

### Mitigation and Counteracting Climate Change

#### 1. **Reforestation and Afforestation**

Reforestation (restocking depleted forests) and afforestation (planting trees where none existed) are effective carbon sequestration strategies. A single mature tree can absorb up to 22 kg of CO2 annually and sequester nearly one tonne over 40 years ([Wikipedia, 2020](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deforestation_and_climate_change)).

China’s afforestation efforts have increased forest coverage from 12% in the 1980s to over 23% in 2021, demonstrating the potential for large-scale forest restoration ([Wikipedia, 2020](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deforestation_and_climate_change)).

#### 2. **Sustainable Forest Management**

Reduced impact logging (RIL) decreases canopy damage and supports faster forest regeneration, reducing emissions from timber harvesting ([Wikipedia, 2020](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deforestation_and_climate_change)).

#### 3. **Agroforestry**

Integrating trees into agricultural landscapes improves biodiversity, soil health, and carbon storage, while supporting livelihoods ([Wikipedia, 2020](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deforestation_and_climate_change)).

#### 4. **REDD+ Initiatives**

Reducing Emissions from Deforestation and Forest Degradation (REDD+) provides financial incentives to conserve forests, promoting sustainable management and reforestation, particularly in developing countries ([Grantham Research Institute, 2018](https://www.lse.ac.uk/granthaminstitute/explainers/what-is-the-role-of-deforestation-in-climate-change-and-how-can-redd-help/)).

---

### Conclusion

Deforestation is a significant driver of climate change through multiple interconnected mechanisms. It directly releases large quantities of CO2, reduces the planet’s capacity to sequester carbon, alters biophysical processes that regulate temperature and precipitation, and impacts atmospheric chemistry via short-lived climate forcers. The scale of deforestation, especially in tropical regions, makes it a critical target for climate mitigation.

Mitigating deforestation through sustainable land use, reforestation, afforestation, and international policy mechanisms like REDD+ is essential to curb global warming. While fossil fuel emissions remain the dominant source of greenhouse gases, addressing deforestation is a vital complementary strategy to stabilize the climate.

